message: To get high scores, focus on using scissors on 'soft' ingredients. Cutting artificial soft items (yarn, sponge, newspaper, ribbon, cardboard) and natural soft items (mushroom, feather, leaf, sunflower) consistently yields 'cut' items valued at 25. The most effective strategy is to combine *one* 'cut natural-soft' item with *one* 'cut artificial-soft' item; this reliably produces an item valued at 80. Avoid combining more than two 'cut' items, as this often leads to 'overcomplicated' items with greatly reduced value. The 'frame' tool on hard natural items (pinecone, wood) yields a value of 20, but combining two 'framed' items resulted in negative value. Submit when you have an 80-value item.

message: Focus on 'cut' and 'framed' items. Scissors work best on artificial and soft items like thread, yarn, paper, or cardboard, creating 'cut' versions (value 25). Combine these 'cut' items with natural and soft ingredients like flowers or feathers to make valuable new items (around 55). Always try to 'frame' these combined items, as it often boosts their value significantly (up to 75). Be warned: combining two items that are *already framed* usually leads to 'overcomplicated' items with 'ruined frames' and heavily negative values. Avoid that trap! Also, 'beads' can combine well with natural items, and then framing those beaded items can be good. Good luck!
